#Text=DS : How would psychoanalysis handle something like Obsessive-compulsive disorder ?
#Text=It seems like the treatments that have been most successful are behavioral-cognitive and SSRI therapy .
#Text=JM :
#Text=I think we have to cede ground on that .
#Text=As a psychiatrist who is analytically trained , I like to think of myself as a dynamic psychiatrist .
#Text=Meaning that I use some of the theories that we have talked about to help inform my approach to a patient , but I importantly also consider my medical and psychiatric knowledge .
#Text=In the case of OCD , the preferred treatments are often medication and cognitive behavioral therapy .
#Text=I recently worked with an OCD individual , at the insistence of his behavior therapist who wanted me to help the individual figure out why he was having a hard time accepting medication .
#Text=In the end , frankly , I referred him back to the behavioral therapist because our treatment was n't going anywhere .
#Text=Gender identity and Heteronormativity
#Text=DS : How do you explain the exaggerated femininity of some gay men ?
#Text=JM : It 's a complex question and I do not have an easy answer .
#Text=I think some of it is political , some of it is provocative , and some of it is genuine .
#Text=I think that there are people who are naturally feminine .
#Text=We all come in different flavors and colors , and it 's the same in terms of our personality tributes , whether male or female .
#Text=There are some heterosexual women who are more masculine , and some heterosexual men who are more feminine .
#Text=The same with gay men .
#Text=In addition to that , some of it is a provocative stance , certainly earlier on back when it was more of a ' fuck you ' attitude than it might need to be today .

#Text=For example , drag queens or the front of the gay pride parade , which is more of a very in-your-face , we are here , we are comfortable with who we are , and we can be as provocative as we can be because we are who we are , and we are entitled to be this way .
#Text=DS : Chris Crocker , the YouTube celebrity known for his in-your-face femininity , perhaps falls in that category .

#Text=JM : Look at the other side of it , some of the rappers who epitomize raw masculinity in an in-your-face kind of way , and I would see that as the other end of the spectrum , but doing a similar thing .
#Text=A ' fuck you ' kind of attitude , ' I have the right to be who I am ' kind of thing .
#Text=There 's a whole spectrum , and most of us fall in the middle .
#Text=DS : What is the process by which a person develops a gender ?
#Text=JM : It 's complex .
#Text=Part of it is genetic endowment .
#Text=Nature versus nurture .
#Text=Part of it is what we come from , who we come from , and that , together with the environment in which we grow .

#Text=For example , we can have a genetic endowment that predisposes us towards femininity , but we are nurtured in a family that is extremely orthodox , ' you 're a boy , so you 're going to be a man . '
#Text=That kid may grow up to be a rather straight , but conflicted , kind of individual .
#Text=A macho kind of guy , or a macho gay guy , may have some conflict around the environment he grew up in .
#Text=I think it 's an amalgam of genetics , our environment we grow up in , and whatever experiences we come across along the way .
#Text=That 's what fine tunes that individual into what he or she will become .
